<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=100210350554183></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f100210350554183><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=4&mid=100210350554183>Barding</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=4&mid=100210350554183#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=56786><span id= >Soberion</span></a>, <span id= > </span><br><span id=notbold>8 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Wed, Oct 3rd 6:05 AM 2001</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Excellent<span id=notbold>[5.00]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>Heya folks.&nbsp;&nbsp;Soberion Everday here, currently a level 50 bard on Ayonae Ro server.  If you want to bard, here are what I think are some tips.<br><br>First, ignore anyone who says a bard is a jack of all trades.  That is an insult to barding.  As a bard, you'll one day be a master of song.  Forget all that jack stuff.  They use that to throw you off.  ;)<br><br>Attributes you need at creation time are charisma first & dexterity second.  Discussion as to race & exact attribute mix can go on forever, but I don't think anyone will ever create a best bard.  CHA + DEX, in the amounts of your choice, will surely make for a respectable showing no matter how you bias it.<br><br>For combat, you need all 1H and hand-to-hand as well.  You'll be pretty lousy in melee until level 38, so being able to match weapon to foe (for instance, use blunt against skellies) will be valuable, especially in close fights where every point counts.  As well, as you advance higher and higher, going instrumental in combat will be more and more productive, which is why you need hand-to-hand.  High-level fights are often as close as low ones, and being able to punch a drolvarg captain for 9 hp every round for 30 rounds is indeed a good thing, since that is damage ADDED to what you're doing for your party with song.<br><br>All weapon skills and instrument skills need to be acquired and practiced as much as possible.  At first, you won't be able to get them maxed for each level, much less keep them there.  After a while, though, you'll be able to do it easily.  The formula is (char level + 1) * 5 for all but hand-to-hand, which is (char level + 1) * 3 for some reason.  (Not to mention a few that leave off the + 1, like Offense & Defense.)  Instrument skills you can practice by leaving your char on while you sleep or take a shower or whatever.  The hard one is Brass because until level 42 it's strictly offensive.  Any out-of-the-way place will cure that problem.  Before 42, I always went to the far corner of a newbie zone for Brass practice.  The newbs got free corpse loot & I got skill, a simple equation.<br><br>Throwing is an under-rated skill for a bard.  It's great for pulling when you don't have a pull song memed, but frankly most bards don't bother with it.  I have it maxed (113) because I'm obsessed with being perfect.  LOL.  You can do it, too, if you like.  :)<br><br>Instill Doubt is taught only by the Guild Master in Freeport.  It will save your tail a few times & is well worth acquiring & practicing.<br><br>Dual Wield at 17 & Tracking at 35 are essential skills to acquire & develop.<br><br>Also, count on all of the following to help you as a bard or simply as an EQ char :  bind wound, forage, hide, sense heading, swimming, sneak, sense traps, safe fall, & pick lock.  They aren't all essential & some are more important than others.  Bind wound, sense heading, swimming & safe fall are the best from this list.<br><br>Learn to weave songs as soon as possible, & forget about weaving more than 3 at a time unless you have far better equipment & connectivity than all but one person I've ever actually met playing the game.  My experience shows me I can weave 2 almost perfectly and 3 pretty darn well.  I do use the occasional 4-weave, but not often.  Three is standard.  It has worked fairly well thus far.<br><br>At level 34, assuming you have Velious, you can get the Cantata of Soothing and find out why a bard would ever consider going instrumental.  This song, woven with 1 or 2 more songs of your choice, can keep your party in mana, health & vigor for as long as you all care to fight.  Use the heads-up view (press F10 once) and you can make use of the additional 4 hot-button slots to enable instrument weaving to match your song weaving.  When you first get FULL song effects by weaving instruments to match your songs, you'll see what a bard can really be & why top-level groups want you around.<br><br>Last but not least, I suggest you do your best to avoid all groups where you're nothing but a mana battery.  Mana generation is a BIG part of barding, but to reduce a bard to only that function is about as smart as using the Atlantic Ocean only to get shrimp.  I can't count on all my fingers & toes the groups I've left (& I TELL them this!) because that's all they want me for.  The only folks who really hate this is the mana junkies who never learn to manage their own use of the stuff.  In terms of their own education, they're better off with NO mana supplier, so leave them & find a group with a brain whenever you can.  It usually isn't too hard, & even when it is, I've found it to be worth it most of the time.  ;)<br><br>Ah, what else?  Oh yeah, run fast.  Don't forget that.  Run fast.  :)<br><br>If you're bard enough to actually earn all your own lambent, you'll be a pretty good bard.  It'll take a while, but all I've met who've done it are, well, a different breed of bard than most.<br><br>Good luck & good barding.  Enjoy.  :)<br>&nbsp;<br>Soberion, wood-elven bard of no great skill but ever-hopeful.&nbsp;&nbsp;;)</td></tr>
