<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=100206065238765></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f100206065238765><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=4&mid=100206065238765>The Unsung Bard (No Pun Intended)</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=4&mid=100206065238765#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <span id= >Anonymous</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Tue, Oct 2nd 6:10 PM 2001</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Excellent<span id=notbold>[4.50]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2><br>Although my alts will remain anon, I will say that I have played every class in Everquest to some extent, and I must say, the Bard was the class that took me by surprise.<br><br>I'll admit, that before I gave the Bard a shot, I was very unsure. <br><br>About a week ago, I started on a new server for myself, (Seventh Hammer) and created Talesin, my now level 12 Bard.&nbsp;&nbsp;With a tp from a generous highbie, I was able to get to NK and then ran on to Qeynos.  (Personal favorite area to hunt)<br><br>After the first couple of levels, I was still feeling a bit strange.  I wasn't quite sure how to play this mix of classes, this jack of all trades.  It wasn't until I picked up the Bard's different instruments that I finally began to understand the Bard's strange mix.  So here goes:<br><br>The Bard is a tool.  Sounds strange, but stay with me.  The bard is a tool in a group.  He does what is needed.  I'll get to some examples in a moment.  The Bard is the "Leatherman" so to speak.  Many, many, many uses.  From fighting in areas like QH, NK and Blackburrow, I have been able to use some of my abilities to the fullest, and develop some strategies that I don't believe alot of non-bards understand.  Most people want to see results.  NOW.  Fast, obvious results that even the local idiot could see (alot of those on Everyquest these days it seems but that's beside the point)<br><br>By hunting ONLY to level 12, going on 13, I've come to the conclusion that the bard one of the most, if not THE most useful class in Norrath.  Let's look at the definition of the bard.  A traveling minstral, a singer, and entertainer.  He brings joy to people's lives whether it be acting, poetry, acrobatics, motivation, the list goes on.  And that is exactly what the Bard does.<br><br>Example one:<br>As a bard, you have Hymn of Restoration.  A basic overview is that it's a song that will regen life at a low rate, but can be increased byt he use of stringed instruments, ect.  At low levels, this is THE MOST fantastic song to play.  Play it ALL the time in a group.  The reaosn is simple, but hard for some to understand.  Pick up your lute bards, and try playing Hymn for an entire battle, without twisting.  With the lute, you should be able to regen about 8-9 hp per pulse.  Now, I know what your're thinking/  That's not much right?  Wrong.<br><br>9hp per pulse adds up to a TON.  If the mob misses you, you add an extra 9hp back....if the mob HITS your tank for 12 points of damage, in reality he's only taken 3 points.  Let's say you and a tank are fighting an Elite Gnoll Guard in Blackburrow.  They can hit for about for a fair amount of damage.  Sometimes upwards for 24.  But, they miss alot.  Let's say that the elite hits your tank for about 10 damage...you've cancelled out 9 of that already.  Everytime he misses, you give your tank 9hp back.  misses again and there's 18.  It adds up drastically.  By the end of the fight, let's say for kicks, 20 "rounds" of combat.  9 times 20 is 180.  You've saved your tank 180 hp.  Although this may be trivial at higher levels, at low levels, it's fantastic past any buffs you might be able to give the party.<br><br>One of the most underrated battle songs in the Bard's song book is Selo's Accelerando.  I know what you're thinking.  "What the hell?" right?  Well, hear me out, because I've used this technique several times, and each time it has been effective....especially if you are outside in an open area.<br><br>Let'spretend that yoru tank or whomever makes a mispull.  Happens to everyone.  Usually death comes of it, but not anymore.  Our poor tank has 6 mobs on him ( *sniff*  <br><br>Well, this is when we bards can be used as a tool as I was talking about earlier )  Take out your melee weapon and hit four or five of the mobs.  I know what you're thinking again (What the hell?) but pay attention.  Since you have a fair amount of hp, you'll be able to take some of these hits.  Back them off yoru tank.  Then take out your drum, and sing Selo's.<br><br>Then RUN away.  The mobs will follow you, but they won't be able to catch up.  This gives your group time to off the two that are still aggro'ed while you lead the extra mobs on a wild goose chase taking no damage whatsoever besides the initial tank damage.  When your group is ready, bring them back and have your tanks and casters pull a couple off of you, then run again.  Repeat.  <br><br>You have to be careful using this technique and be on the lookout for casters, who will zap you down.  To avoid this, simply have your tanks aggro the caster&lt;s&gt;.  Another thing to worry about are the trains.  Well, if they're chasing you, just keep running.  When your party calls for more, bring a couple and let them aggro a few.  Repeat.  Sounds crazy, but it works by God.<br><br>Those are just a few unsung uses of the Bard.  Remember before you start to rip Bards, that WE ALREADY KNOW we aren't the best at anything.  But we are multi-talented, and more so than you.  If you rip bards, then you A: Have never played one B: Played with a bard who didn't have a clue or C: Don't understand them.<br><br>Perfectly ok though.  Understandable.  Try one out and you'll understand.  So, as advice to all Bards, USE your effectiveness.  For God's sake don't be afraid to put away your melee weapon and enhance some effects.  Don't be afraid to step in a take a couple of hits if your tank if getting low.  Don't be afraid to Aggro some mobs and run them away from your party until a later date.  The problem with Bards is that alot of people don't understand how to play them.  Playing a Bard takes a great deal of creativity.  You CAN DO WHAT EVER YOU WANT.  Be creative.  Find new ways to aid your party other than just sitting on your ass and buffing.  <br><br>Bards around the world unite!  And don't be afraid of those instruments )<br><br>                           Talesin<br>                          12th Level<br>                        Seventh Hammer<br><br>(Mostly directed to newbies and other Bard doubters)<br>&nbsp;<br> </td></tr>
